##User Defined Functions

#Converting factor to numeric
as.num.fact <- function(x) {as.numeric(as.character(x))}

#Calculate difference in means as a percentage of standard deviation for continuous variables

cont_mean_pct_sd <- function(x){
  
  when_1 <- mean(final_data[final_data$num == 1, x])
  
  when_0 <- mean(final_data[final_data$num == 0, x])
  
  sd_pool     <- sd(final_data[,x])
  
  return( (when_1 - when_0)*100/sd_pool  )
}

#Calculate p_value for continuous variables

cont_p_value <- function(x){
  t.test(final_data[final_data$num == 1, x], final_data[final_data$num == 0, x])$p.value
}


#Calculate scaled mean for categorical variables
cat_mean_pct_sd <- function(x){
  
  when_1 <- mean(as.num.fact((filter(final_data,!!as.symbol(x) == 1) %>% dplyr::select(num))$num))
  
  when_0 <- mean(as.num.fact((filter(final_data,!!as.symbol(x) == 0) %>% dplyr::select(num))$num))
  
  sd_pool <- sd(as.num.fact(final_data$num ))
  return( (when_1 - when_0)*100/sd_pool  )
  
}


#P-value for categorical variables
cat_p_value <- function(x){
  
  return(t.test(as.num.fact((filter(final_data,!!as.symbol(x) == 1) %>% dplyr::select(num))$num) ,  as.num.fact((filter(final_data,!!as.symbol(x) == 0) %>% dplyr::select(num))$num)  )$p.value)
}

#Concordance between two categorical variables

concord_cat <- function(x, y){
  
  first = final_data[, x]
  second = final_data[, y]
  return(sum(first == second)*100/297)
  
  
}

##Remove outlier from a df given a column and return df without outliers

var_remove_outliers <- function(x,df ){
  
  stage_df <- df
  
  out <- integer(0)
  
  if(is.numeric(stage_df[,x])){
    
    out <- which(abs(stage_df[, x]) >( abs( mean(stage_df[, x])) + abs((3*sd(stage_df[, x])))) )
    
  }
  
  if(length(out) > 0){
    
    stage_df <- stage_df[-out,]
  }
  return(stage_df)
  
  
}
##Standardize continuous variables by centering and dividing by 2*SD

var_scale <- function(x){return((x - mean(x))/(2*sd(x)))}


##Normalize a variable
var_norm <- function(x){return((x - mean(x))/(sd(x)))}

Introduction

In this notebook I apply different statistical and machine learning techniques to understand the relationship between Coronary Heart Disease and various features assocaited with it using a publicly available dataset. I use the Cleveland Heart Study dataset made available in the UC Irvine Machine Learning Repository.

There are three important caveats regarding the scope of this exercise that I wish to state at the very beginning:

  1. Although I apply some techniques that are associated causal inference, it is not possible to make a causal claim regarding heart disease using this dataset for two reasons:

  • First, the dataset deals with an observational study and not an experimental one. That is there is no randomly assigned treatment variable that we can exploit to estimate an average causal effect.

  • Second, I have no domain expertise or specific knowledge of cardiology or for that matter medicine. So I am unable to build a structural casual model using the available features that would allow for estimation of causal relationships.

  1. Therefore the scope of this study is strictly restricted to analysing the association relationship in the dataset using my knowledge of statistics and machine learning. Since the dataset comes from a hospital in Cleveland, it maybe safe to assume that it is a representative sample of patients at risk of heart disease. Therefore, the associational claims maybe generalisable to such a population.

  2. The larger purpose of this exercise is to demonstrate how statistics and machine learning can be applied for inference and distilling insights from data.

With those caveats in place, I shall proceed as follows. The notebook is divided into three parts. In Part 1, I explore the features in the dataset, pre-process them, and look at naive associational relationships between each feature (independent variables) and the response variable (dependent variable).

Part 1: Feature Processing and Naive Associational Relationships

In this section, I first remove rows with null values (there are only 6 out of 303) and then I examine each feature in the data set to better understand its meaning, distribution, and association with heart disease. In the dataset there are 9 categorical variables (including the response variable) and 5 continuous variables. In order to simplify the analysis, where reasonably possible I reduce categorical variables with multiple categories to a dichotomous variable without significant loss of information.I begin by applying this to the response variable. Then I look at the naive association between that feature and the response variable. I call this naive in contrast to other analyses because I looks at the relationship without conditioning on other features. This provides a primer for more sophisticated analyses in later sections. At the end of this section, I propose a metric to compare each features relationship to the response variable.

NB: For each feature, I use the definition provided in the data dictionary with the variable name as coded in the dataset in parantheses.

1. Diagnosis of Heart Disease (num)

This is the response variable for my analysis. It is categorical variable that takes any of values from 0 to 4. However, the data dictionary only mentions 0 for less than 50% reduction in diameter and 1 for > 50% reduction. Therefore, I convert all values greater than 0 to 1. This can be interpreted as a 1 indicating diagnosis of heart disease and 0 indicating no diagnosis. Below I plot the distribution after processing the variable.

##This is prima-facie a surprising result since it indicates that patients with chest pain of any type seem o have lower occurrence of heart disease
##Nonetheless given the limited variation in heart disease Diagnosis  for those exibhiting pain, I code asymptomatic as 0 and the rest as 1

clean_data <- mutate(clean_data,
                     cp_clean = as.factor(if_else(cp == 4, 0 ,1)))

It can be observed that patients reporting Asymptomatic account for almost half of the dataset. However, it also seems that those reported as Asymptomatic have a much higher probability of being diagnosed with heart disease compared to those reporting ny type of chest pain. This is prima-facie a counter-intuitive result since Anginal pain is a major symptom of coronary heart disease (from quick googling!). This could be due to an error in the coding of this feature in the data dictionary or due to something specific to how the data was collected. Nonetheless, there is no way to determine why this is the case and I wil choose to trust the data as is.

Since there are 4 different categories, it is worth exploring if this can be reduced to a dichotomous variable. Given the limited variation in the association between different types of pain and diagnosis of heart disease and the three types of pain together account for slightly more than 50% of data, I code this feature as 1 for presence of chest pain and 0 for Asymptomatic/no pain.

Comparing The Naive Association of Features with Heart Disease Diagnosis

As conclusion to Part 1, I shall provide a framework to compare the features on their association with heart disease diagnosis. This frameworks uses two different but related metrics for categorical and continuous features.

Continuous Variables

For continuous variables, first I calculate the difference in arithmetic means for that variable between the cohort of patients diagnosed with heart disease versus the cohort that has not been diagnosed with heart disease. I express this as a percentage of the pooled standard deviation of that variable. I also check to ensure this difference is statistically significant using a two sided t-Test. This is a useful way to compare the importance of these features relative to each other. Larger the absolute value greater is the associational importance of that variable.

I call this metric Importance and use \(\Delta_{CONT}\) to denote it. Mathematically defined below:

\({\Delta_{CONT}(Var) = \dfrac{({\mu_{Var | H = 1}^{\hat{}} - \mu_{Var| H = 0}^{\hat{}}})}{\sqrt{\sigma_{Var}^{2}}} \times 100}\)

Below I plot all the continuous features on their absolute value of \(\Delta_{CONT}\).

Click here For Code/Plots

##Conclusion to Part 2

#After cleaning and testing for naive associations, I find that 10 out of the 13 show some form of statistically significant association with heart disease based on t test for difference in means

Categorical Variables

For categorical variables, I first compute the proportion of patients with a heart diagnosis in each category. Since I re-coded all categorical variables as dichotomous, I compute the difference in proportions when the variable is 1 and when it is 0. In most cases 0 indicated Normal; so we can think of the difference as an effect. I perform a t-Test to check for statistical significance and express the difference as a percentage of the overall standard deviation in the proportion of patients diagnosed with heart disease. Similar to the metric for continuous variables, this gives us a useful way to study the relative importance of categorical variables on the basis of their association with heart disease diagnosis.

I call this metric Importance and use \(\Delta_{CAT}\) to denote it. Mathematically defined below:

\({\Delta_{CAT}(Var) = \dfrac{({\mu_{H | Var = 1}^{\hat{}} - \mu_{H| Var = 0}^{\hat{}}})}{\sqrt{\sigma_{H}^{2}}} \times 100}\)

Below I plot all the continuous features on their absolute value of \(\Delta_{CAT}\).

Part 2: Conditional Effect of Features Using Generalized Linear Models

In the last part, we examined the unconditional relationship between the features and diagnosis of heart disease. We found that most of features had some effect on diagnosis of heart disease. However, this importance may diminish on conditioning on other features. This maybe true especially if some of the features are correlated with others. Two correlated variables may seem to be both important based on unconditional association, but taken together do not provide more information. Therefore by examining the conditional relationship, I build on the previous section.

In this section, I investigate the conditional relationship between the features and the response variable using the logistic regression model. Logistic regression is applicable to cases where the response variable is dichotomous, i.e.a binary outcome. Although logistic regression requires fewer assumptions than OLS linear regression, there are a couple of important ones worth noting.

  1. There must exist a linear relationship between the features and the log-odds of the dichotomous response variable. Note that this does not require a linear relationship between the features and the response, but between the features and the log-odds of the response. Log-odds refers to logarithm of the odds-ratio, which is ratio of probability of success by probability of failure. In our case the odds ratio would be ratio of probability of being diagnosed with heart disease by the probability of no heart disease diagnosis. I shall examine the interpretation of this term further when we analyze the coefficients of the logistic model. There is no real way to test whether this linear relationship between log odds and the features hold, so I shall press forward having noted this caveat.

  2. The independent variables (features) should be independent of each other and not be heavily correlated. When this is not true the regression estimates are often unstable and tend to have large standard errors. While we can be reasonably confident that the features are independent of each other, that is they measure different things, we need to check the correlations among the continuous variables and concordance among categorical variables. I check for these in the next section.

  3. Continuous features should not have significant outliers and should be standardized to ensure easy comparison of coefficients. Significant outliers can drive the fitting of the model leading to faulty estimates. I define outliers as those with values greater than 3 standard deviations from the mean and I remove any rows with an outlier. Further, I standardize the continuous variables using the method suggested by Andrew Gelman. This involves centering all continuous variable values by subtracting the mean and dividing by twice the standard deviation. This makes the coefficient estimates between continuous and categorical variables readily comparable.

In this section, I check for correlations between continuous variables and concordance between categorical variables. I define concordance between two binary categorical variables as the percentage of their values that are exactly the same, i.e they are both 1s or both 0s. Below I display the results.

Fitting a logistic regression model

As mentioned earlier, before fitting a logistic regression model it is imperative to remove outliers among continuous variables and standardize them according to the method proposed earlier. After these transformations, I proceed to fit a naive model with all the features included in the specification. Thereafter, I perform step-wise variable selection using AIC (Akaike Information Criteria). This iterates through the feature set, iteratively adding as well as removing features, and identifies the model with lowest AIC. Below I report the coefficient estimates from both models.

The table above shows the coefficients of each feature for two of the regressions specified. Empty cells indicate that the Step-wise selection method dropped the variable. p-Values in bold are < 0.05 and indicate that we can reject the null hypothesis that the effect of the feature is 0 (or 1 in odds-ratio terms).

For continuous features, the odds-ratio maybe interpreted as the change in probability of being diagnosed with heart disease for a unit change in the concerned feature holding all other features at the same value. From the table we can see that none of the continuous features turn out to be significant. For the sake of understanding the logic of interpretation, lets assume that Cholesterol level feature was significant. This would mean that for a unit positive change in Cholesterol Levels holding all other features constant, the probability of being diagnosed with heart disease would increase by 109% or 1.09 times relative to the probability of no heart disease diagnosis. In this case since I standardized our continuous variables, a unit change would be a 2 standard deviation change. While this specification makes the coefficients of categorical and continuous features comparable,

For categorical features, the interpretation is similar but instead of a unit change, it would mean a change in category with all other features being held constant. From the table we can see that feature Colored Vessels has the largest statistically significant effect with an odds-ratio of 8.19 in the Step-wise model. This means that if a person were to go from no colored vessels(0) to at least one colored vessel (1) while none of the other features change, the probability of being diagnosed with heart disease would increase by 719% or 7.09 times relative to the probability of no heart disease diagnosis. Now consider the feature Reported Chest Pain which shows an odds ratio of 0.15, which is statistically significant. This would mean that a patient who changes from not reporting chest pain to reporting chest pain with all other features remaining the same, the probability of being diagnosed with heart disease would decrease by 85% or 0.85 times relative to the probability of no heart disease diagnosis.

Using these regression estimates, we can conclude that when conditioned on all available features, an increase in probability of heart disease diagnosis relative to no heart disease diagnosis is associated with a change in category (from 0 to 1) of Colored Vessels, Thalium Test, Slope of ST-Segment, and Sex. The former three implies a symptomatic/abnormal test result whereas the latter implies a change in sex from female to male. Similarly, we can also conclude that a change from reporting no chest pain to reporting chest pain is associated with a decrease in probability of heart disease diagnosis relative to no heart disease diagnosis. I also ran checks to ensures there is no multi-collinearity (correlation among features) inflating the variance of any of the features using the VIF test. All the VIF estimates for features were below 2; any value above 5 is a cause for concern.

Part 3: Feature Importance using Machine Learning Algorithms

In this section, I will use two machine learning algorithms optimized to predict diagnosis of heart disease. Although predictive power is not of importance for this analysis, these algorithms allow for ranking features based on their relative importance in predicting the response variable. These techniques are also better at identifying non-linear relationships and interactions between features compared to previous techniques. These models deal with the Bias-Variance trade-off much better than normal regression techniques which are constrained by seeking to compute unbiased estimates even at the cost of high variance. Therefore, this appraoch truly exploits machine intelligence with far less intervention from my end in contrast to previous sections.

I shall employ a LASSO Logistic Regression and a Random Forest model with hyperparameter optimization through k-fold cross-validation on the training set. After determinig the model of best fit, I shall rank the features in terms of their relative importance in each model. I also report the performance of both models on a common test set.

LASSO Logistic Regression

LASSO Logistic Regression is a powerful yet simple machine learning algorithm that is similar to a logistic regression in its basic structure. However, it includes a penalty term hyper-parameter(\(\lambda\)) that works to shrink the coefficient of features to zero to ensure optimal trade-off between bias and variance to ensure maximum predictive power. Thus, it also works as a test of association between features and the response variable. However, the estimated coefficients of features are not very useful or interpretable since by design they are biased (due to the penalty). Therefore I shall not report these coefficient estimates. Nonetheless, there are generalizable, model agnostic technique to determine the relative importance of the features. I am not entirely familiar with the mathematics behind these techniques; I rely on the vip (Variable Importance Plots) Package in R to produce these figures.

Click here For Code/Plots

##Part 3: Variable Importance from Machine Learning
##Lasso logistic 



##I train a logistic regression model to predict probaility of heart disease diagnosis and determine the important variables

##Splitting data into training and testing set; i use a 90/10 split since I do not care that much about prediction but want to keep as much data as possible fo training
set.seed(789)

#Normalizing continuous variables 
final_data_norm <- final_data %>% mutate(across(where(is.numeric), var_norm ))

final_data_split <- initial_split(final_data_norm, prop = 0.9)

final_data_train <- training(final_data_split)

final_data_test <- testing(final_data_split)

train_iv_matrix <- model.matrix(num~., final_data_train)[,-1]

train_dv <- as.num.fact(final_data_train$num)

##Setting up cross validation

cv_lasso <- cv.glmnet(train_iv_matrix, train_dv, alpha = 1, family ="binomial")

###Specifying best fit model using samllest best cross validated parameter estimate

lasso_model_min <- glmnet(train_iv_matrix, train_dv, alpha = 1, family = "binomial", lambda = cv_lasso$lambda.min  )

lasso_importance <- vi(lasso_model_min)

lasso_importance <- mutate(lasso_importance,
                           Variable = as.factor(Variable)) %>% mutate(Variable = fct_reorder(Variable, (Importance)))

lasso_imp_plot <- ggplot(lasso_importance) +
  geom_col(aes(Variable, Importance, fill = Importance)) +
  scale_y_continuous(breaks = seq(-2,2,0.4))+
  scale_x_discrete(name = "Features", label = c("Reported Chest Pain", "Max Heart Rate Acheived", "Age", "Fasting Blood Sugar","Cholestrol Level", "Induced ST Depression","Resting Blood Pressure" ,"Resting ECG","Exercise Induced Angina" ,"Sex","Slope of ST Segment", "Thalium Test", "Colored Vessels")) +
  coord_flip()+
  ggtitle("Feature Importance from LASSO Logistic Regression")


###Making Predictions
test_iv_matrix <- model.matrix(num~., final_data_test)[,-1]

test_dv <- as.num.fact(final_data_test$num)

lasso_predict <- predict(lasso_model_min, newx = test_iv_matrix)

lasso_prob <- if_else(lasso_predict>0.5,1,0)

mean(lasso_prob == test_dv)
## [1] 0.7931034
#Lasso has an accuracy of ~80%!!
lasso_imp_plot

After hyper-parameter tuning through cross-validation, the LASSO model performs quite well in predicting diagnosis of heart disease. Even without tuning the threshold value (I round values >0.5 to 1 and the rest to zero) the model has a accuracy of almost 80%. More importantly, the model provides an importance estimate for each feature as seen in the plot above. This result seems to be identical to the one from ordinary logistic regression. Colored Vessels, Thalium Test, Slope of ST Segment, and Sex seem to be the most important feature associated with increased chance of heart disease diagnosis; Reported Chest Pain seems to be the most important variable associated with a decreased chance of heart disease diagnosis. The fact that this model entirely agrees with the ordinary logistic regression should not come as a surprise since they both have similar structure, even if different optimization strategies. Nonetheless, this adds greater weight to the conclusions from the earlier section.

Random Forest Model

Random Forest is an ensemble learning method that has become one of the most, if not the most, popular machine learning technique. They are known to perform very well in classification tasks and provide lots of opportunities for optimization with at least three hyper-parameters that can be tuned. They are excellent at picking up on non-linear relationships and interactions between features that are beyond the scope of linear models. This is the main reason for them being included in this analysis. Through their application I hope to uncover insights that may have eluded earlier techniques.

In applying this method, I do not try to fully optimize it for predictive power. Of the three main hyper-parameters m_Trys, min_n, and number of trees I shall try to tune the first two through k-fold cross validation optimizing for AUC. I play around with different number of trees, but do not seek to systematically tune it for performance since our objective is not prediction. Below I report the model accuracy and Feature Importance plots.

Click here For Code/Plots

## Random forest

set.seed(1972)

##Copying the same data set as LASSO
forest_train <- final_data_train

forest_test <- final_data_test

forest_cv <- vfold_cv(forest_train, v = 5)

##Prepaing the model spec and prepping; continuous variables have already been normalized

forest_recipe <- recipe(num~., data = forest_train) 

forest_recipe_prepped <- forest_recipe  %>% prep(data = forest_train)

forest_juiced <- juice(forest_recipe_prepped)

##Specify the model and engine

forest_tune_spec <- rand_forest(
                                mtry = tune(),
                                trees = 5,
                                min_n = tune()
                                ) %>% set_mode("classification") %>%
                                                                    set_engine("ranger")



##Creating workflow

forest_tune_wf <- workflow() %>% add_recipe(forest_recipe) %>% add_model(forest_tune_spec)

doParallel::registerDoParallel()

##Tuning Hyper parameters mtry and n using cross validation

forest_tune_result <- tune_grid(
                                forest_tune_wf,
                                resamples = forest_cv,
                                grid = 10
)



##Selecting the best model

forest_best <- select_best(forest_tune_result, "roc_auc")

final_forest <- finalize_model(forest_tune_spec, forest_best)

##Identifying important variables

forest_fit <- final_forest %>% set_engine("ranger", importance = "permutation") %>% fit(num~. ,data = forest_juiced)

forest_importance <- vi(forest_fit) 

forest_importance <- mutate(forest_importance,
                           Variable = as.factor(Variable)) %>% mutate(Variable = fct_reorder(Variable, (Importance)))

##Plotting

forest_imp_plot <- ggplot(forest_importance) +
  geom_col(aes(Variable, Importance, fill = Importance)) +
  scale_y_continuous()+
  scale_x_discrete(name = "Features", label = c("Exercise Induced Angina" ,"Cholestrol Level","Resting Blood Pressure","Fasting Blood Sugar","Sex", "Age", "Resting ECG","Slope of ST Segment", "Max Heart Rate Acheived" , "Induced ST Depression", "Thalium Test","Reported Chest Pain", "Colored Vessels")) +
  coord_flip()+
  ggtitle("Feature Importance from Random Forest")


##Looking at accuracy

forest_test_predicted <- predict(forest_fit, new_data = forest_test)

sum(as.num.fact(forest_test$num)==forest_test_predicted$.pred_class)/length(forest_test$num)
## [1] 0.7241379
forest_imp_plot

After some tuning, I settle on a model that has a prediction accuracy of between 70 and 80%, which is not even better than LASSO.

However, the feature importance plot tells a far more interesting story. First of all, it is important to note that these estimates of importance do not seem stable. In running this code chunk a couple of time I have been shown quite different results even though the seed had remained the same. In fact I am not sure if the results will remain the same when I knit this document. Since the model relies on building decision path through random subsets of variables, this is not be expected. Therefore itd be risky to generalize. This also suggests that the model needs to be tuned better.

Second, in comparison to the LASSO model, importance is more tightly distributed among the features; the model is not over-reliant on some features like the LASSO model. Although I am not sure if a direct comparison of values of the Importance estimate is warranted, it is still worth noting that the range of Importance is vastly smaller in scale compared to LASSO. This suggests that some features, although not significant by themselves, become important in conjunction with others. This suggests that there maybe significant non-linear effects and interactions between features that is associated with the response variable.

Third, although the most important features from the LASSO model continue to be important, there are some noteworthy changes in rank. The most conspicuous result seems to be for Reported Chest Pain. This feature has changed from having a strong negative association with the response to a strong positive association. This suggests that the feature maybe producing this effect through interactions with other features or in certain specific cases. Another feature that has similarly changed direction seems to be Maximum Heart Rate achieved which has flipped from being weakly negative associated to positive association.

In conclusion it difficult to take the estimates from the Random Forest model seriously given its instability, especially in comparison to LASSO and Logistic model which are far more stable.
